Introduction

The Monte Calro simulation is mathematical technique that predicts possible outcomes of an uncertain event. Here, the key concept is randomness. As an introduction, using Monte carlo simulation, we get a good approximation of \(\pi\). And then we will use this in a physica problem where we will simulate the collective behaviour of a magnet.

A magnet consists of individual tiny magnets.(For your understanding only, dont take it literally!). And all these magnets can point along all three directions in space, and they insteract with each other. So it means when you try to minimize here or error, then it really takes an enormous amount of time.

So instead, you minimize the error by just randomly reorienting individual magnets and checking if the error has reduced.

And if this is the case, then you accept the chain to change. And if not, then you disregard the change.

And we will really try this for this magnet and we will see that it brings about a lot of advantages.

Measure the are ratio by counting randomly generated points.

points = 100000

rand = 2*np.random.rand(2*points) -1
rand_points = rand.reshape(points, 2)

norm_points_sqr = rand_points[:,0]**2 + rand_points[:,1]**2

points_in = rand_points[norm_points_sqr <= 1]
points_out = rand_points[norm_points_sqr > 1]

pi_approx = 4*len(points_in)/points

print('Approximated pi value = %f'%(pi_approx))
## Approximated pi value = 3.138720
print('Pi in numpy = %f'%(np.pi ))
## Pi in numpy = 3.141593

Preparing my canvas

figure = plt.figure()
ax = figure.add_subplot(111, aspect='equal')


circle = patches.Circle((0,0),1, facecolor = 'none', edgecolor='blue')
ax.add_patch(circle)

plt.grid(False)
plt.xlim([-1.1,1.1])
## (-1.1, 1.1)
plt.ylim([-1.1,1.1])
## (-1.1, 1.1)
plt.scatter(
  points_in[:,0], points_in[:,1],
  color = 'green', s = 0.5 
)

plt.scatter(
  points_out[:,0], points_out[:,1],
  color = 'red', s = 0.05
)

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 0], marker='o', color='k', label=" 1 unit radius")

plt.title("Monte Carlo Approximation of $\pi$")

plt.legend()
plt.show()
